Detect Cycle Entry in Linked List — Floyd’s Algorithm (Tortoise & Hare)

Goal: Return the node where the cycle begins; otherwise return null.
Approach:

Phase 1 (Detect): Move slow by 1 and fast by 2. If they meet, a cycle exists.
Phase 2 (Find Entry): Reset slow to head, then move both one step each; the node where they meet is the cycle’s entry.


Complexity:

Time: O(n)
Space: O(1)


Edge Cases: head == null, single node without cycle → return null.
Pitfall to avoid: In Phase 2, ensure both pointers move one step (not two).


public class Solution {
    public ListNode detectCycle(ListNode head) {
        if(head==null || head.next==null) return null;
        ListNode slow = head;
        ListNode fast = head;
        while(fast!= null && fast.next!=null){
            slow=slow.next;
            fast = fast.next.next;
            if(slow==fast){
                slow = head;
                while (slow!=fast){
                    slow=slow.next;
                    fast=fast.next;
                }
                 return fast;
            }
           
        }
        return null;
        
    }
}
